# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: seaborn-viz
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] In descriptive statistics, a **box plot** or **boxplot** is a method for demonstrating graphically the locality, spread and skewness groups of numerical data through their quartiles.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] In addition to the box on a box plot, there can be lines (which are called *whiskers*) extending from the box indicating variability outside the upper and lower quartiles, thus, the plot is also called the **box-and-whisker plot** and the **box-and-whisker diagram**.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Outliers that differ significantly from the rest of the dataset may be plotted as individual points beyond the whiskers on the box plot.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Box plots are non-parametric: they display variation in samples of a statistical population without making any assumptions of the underlying statistical distribution (though Tukey's box plot assumes symmetry for the whiskers and normality for their length).
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The spacings in each subsection of the box plot indicate the degree of dispersion (spread) and skewness of the data, which are usually described using the five-number summary.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] In addition, the box plot allows one to visually estimate various L-estimators, notably the interquartile range, midhinge, range, mid-range, and trimean.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Box plots can be drawn either horizontally or vertically.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The range-bar method was first introduced by Mary Eleanor Spear in her book "Charting Statistics" in 1952 and again in her book "Practical Charting Techniques" in 1969.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The box-and-whisker plot was first introduced in 1970 by John Tukey, who later published on the subject in his book "Exploratory Data Analysis" in 1977.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] A box plot is a standardized way of displaying the dataset based on the five-number summary: the minimum, the maximum, the sample median, and the first and third quartiles.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The box is drawn from *Q*1 to *Q*3 with a horizontal line drawn inside it to denote the median.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Some box plots include an additional character to represent the mean of the data.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The whiskers must end at an observed data point, but can be defined in various ways.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] In the most straightforward method, the boundary of the lower whisker is the minimum value of the data set, and the boundary of the upper whisker is the maximum value of the data set.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Because of this variability, it is appropriate to describe the convention that is being used for the whiskers and outliers in the caption of the box plot.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Another popular choice for the boundaries of the whiskers is based on the 1.5 IQR value.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] From above the upper quartile (***Q*3**), a distance of 1.5 times the IQR is measured out and a whisker is drawn *up to* the largest observed data point from the dataset that falls within this distance.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Similarly, a distance of 1.5 times the IQR is measured out below the lower quartile (***Q*1**) and a whisker is drawn *down to* the lowest observed data point from the dataset that falls within this distance.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Because the whiskers must end at an observed data point, the whisker lengths can look unequal, even though 1.5 IQR is the same for both sides.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] All other observed data points outside the boundary of the whiskers are plotted as **outliers**.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The outliers can be plotted on the box plot as a dot, a small circle, a star, *etc.* (see example below).
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Rarely, box plot can be plotted without the whiskers.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] This can be appropriate for sensitive information to avoid whiskers (and outliers) disclosing actual values observed.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The unusual percentiles 2%, 9%, 91%, 98% are sometimes used for whisker cross-hatches and whisker ends to depict the seven-number summary.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] If the data are normally distributed, the locations of the seven marks on the box plot will be equally spaced.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] On some box plots, a cross-hatch is placed before the end of each whisker.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Tukey first popularized this type of visual data display in 1969, several variations on the classical box plot have been developed, and the two most commonly found variations are the variable-width box plots and the notched box plots.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] One convention for obtaining the boundaries of these notches is to use a distance of $\pm {\frac {1.58{\text{ IQR}}}{\sqrt {n}}}$ around the median.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] For a symmetrical data distribution, the medcouple will be zero, and this reduces the adjusted box plot to the Tukey's box plot with equal whisker lengths of $1.5{\text{ IQR}}$ for both whiskers.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] A series of hourly temperatures were measured throughout the day in degrees Fahrenheit.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] A box plot of the data set can be generated by first calculating five relevant values of this data set: minimum, maximum, median (***Q*2**), first quartile (***Q*1**), and third quartile (***Q*3**).
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The minimum is the smallest number of the data set.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] In this case, the minimum recorded day temperature is 57°F.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The maximum is the largest number of the data set.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] In this case, the maximum recorded day temperature is 81°F.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The median is the "middle" number of the ordered data set.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] This means that exactly 50% of the elements are below the median and 50% of the elements are greater than the median.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The median of this ordered data set is 70°F.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The first quartile value (***Q*1** **or 25th percentile)** is the number that marks one quarter of the ordered data set.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] In other words, there are exactly 25% of the elements that are less than the first quartile and exactly 75% of the elements that are greater than it.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The first quartile value can be easily determined by finding the "middle" number between the minimum and the median.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] For the hourly temperatures, the "middle" number found between 57°F and 70°F is 66°F.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The third quartile value (***Q*3** **or 75th percentile)** is the number that marks three quarters of the ordered data set.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] In other words, there are exactly 75% of the elements that are less than the third quartile and 25% of the elements that are greater than it.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The third quartile value can be easily obtained by finding the "middle" number between the median and the maximum.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] For the hourly temperatures, the "middle" number between 70°F and 81°F is 75°F.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The upper whisker boundary of the box plot is the largest data value that is within 1.5 IQR above the third quartile.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Here, 1.5 IQR above the third quartile is 88.5°F and the maximum is 81°F.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Therefore, the upper whisker is drawn at the value of the maximum, which is 81°F.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Similarly, the lower whisker boundary of the box plot is the smallest data value that is within 1.5 IQR below the first quartile.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Here, 1.5 IQR below the first quartile is 52.5°F and the minimum is 57°F.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Therefore, the lower whisker is drawn at the value of the minimum, which is 57°F.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] In this example, only the first and the last number are changed.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The median, third quartile, and first quartile remain the same.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] In this case, the maximum value in this data set is 89°F, and 1.5 IQR above the third quartile is 88.5°F.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The maximum is greater than 1.5 IQR plus the third quartile, so the maximum is an outlier.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Therefore, the upper whisker is drawn at the greatest value smaller than 1.5 IQR above the third quartile, which is 79°F.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Similarly, the minimum value in this data set is 52°F, and 1.5 IQR below the first quartile is 52.5°F.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] The minimum is smaller than 1.5 IQR minus the first quartile, so the minimum is also an outlier.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Therefore, the lower whisker is drawn at the smallest value greater than 1.5 IQR below the first quartile, which is 57°F.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Using the above example that has 24 data points (*n* = 24), one can calculate the median, first and third quartile either mathematically or visually.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Although box plots may seem more primitive than histograms or kernel density estimates, they do have a number of advantages.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] First, the box plot enables statisticians to do a quick graphical examination on one or more data sets.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Box plots also take up less space and are therefore particularly useful for comparing distributions between several groups or sets of data in parallel.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Lastly, the overall structure of histograms and kernel density estimate can be strongly influenced by the choice of number and width of bins techniques and the choice of bandwidth, respectively.
[src:seaborn-viz/box-plot] Although looking at a statistical distribution is more common than looking at a box plot, it can be useful to compare the box plot against the probability density function (theoretical histogram) for a normal N(0,*σ*2) distribution and observe their characteristics directly.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:seaborn-viz/data-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] On 2 March 2012, ggplot2 version 0.9.0 was released with numerous changes to internal organization, scale construction and layers.
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] On 25 February 2014, Hadley Wickham formally announced that "ggplot2 is shifting to maintenance mode.
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] This means that we are no longer adding new features, but we will continue to fix major bugs, and consider new features submitted as pull requests.
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] In recognition [of] this significant milestone, the next version of ggplot2 will be 1.0.0".
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] In the announcement, it was stated that "ggplot2 now has an official extension mechanism.
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] On 5 July 2018, ggplot2 3.0.0 was released (initially planned as a ggplot2 2.3.0).
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] This now provides support for tidy evaluation allowing quasiquotation in ggplot2 functions.
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] In contrast to base R graphics, ggplot2 allows the user to add, remove or alter components in a plot at a high level of abstraction.
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] This abstraction comes at a cost, with ggplot2 being slower than lattice graphics.
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] Creating separate plots for various subsets of data in base R requires loops and manual management, whereas ggplot2 simplifies that process with a collection of "facet" functions to choose from.
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] One potential limitation of base R graphics is the "pen-and-paper model" utilized to populate the plotting device.
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] Graphical output from the interpreter is added directly to the plotting device or window, rather than separately for each distinct element of a plot.
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] In this respect it is similar to the lattice package, though Wickham argues ggplot2 inherits a more formal model of graphics from Wilkinson.
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] As such, it allows for a high degree of modularity; the same underlying data can be transformed by many different scales or layers.
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] Plots may be created via the convenience function `qplot()` where arguments and defaults are meant to be similar to base R's `plot()` function.
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] More complex plotting capacity is available via `ggplot()` which exposes the user to more explicit elements of the grammar.
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] Wickham posits the success of ggplot2 comes from the increased popularity of the R language and the relative ease of making aesthetically appealing graphics.
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] Along with more serious uses of ggplot2, Wickham also supports the more unusual use cases, like exploring factors for winning in the reality TV show RuPaul's Drag Race.
[src:seaborn-viz/ggplot2] See implementations of The Grammar of Graphics.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] A **heat map** (or **heatmap**) is a two-dimensional data visualization technique that represents the magnitude of individual values within a dataset as a color.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] The variation in color may be by hue or intensity.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] In some applications such as crime analytics or website click-tracking, color is used to represent the *density* of data points rather than a value associated with each point.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] "Heat map" is a relatively new term, but the practice of shading matrices has existed for over a century.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Heat maps originated in 2D displays of the values in a data matrix.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Larger values were represented by small dark gray or black squares (pixels) and smaller values by lighter squares.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] The earliest known example dates to 1873, when Toussaint Loua used a hand-drawn and colored shaded matrix to visualize social statistics across the districts of Paris.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] The idea of reordering rows and columns to reveal structure in a data matrix, known as seriation, was introduced by Flinders Petrie in 1899.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] In 1950, Louis Guttman developed the Scalogram, a method for ordering binary matrices to expose a one-dimensional scale structure.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] In 1957, Peter Sneath displayed the results of a cluster analysis by permuting the rows and the columns of a matrix to place similar values near each other according to the clustering.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] This idea was implemented by Robert Ling in 1973 with a computer program called SHADE.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Ling used overstruck printer characters to represent different shades of gray, one character-width per pixel.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Leland Wilkinson developed the first computer program in 1994 (SYSTAT) to produce cluster heat maps with high-resolution color graphics.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] The Eisen et al. display shown in the figure is a replication of the earlier SYSTAT design.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Software designer Cormac Kinney trademarked the term 'heat map' in 1991 to describe computer software used to display real-time financial market information.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] In 1998 the trademark was acquired by SS&C Technologies, Inc., but the company did not extend the license, so it was annulled in 2006.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] There are two primary categories of heat maps: spatial and grid.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Additionally, there are over ten various types of heat maps.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] A **spatial heat map** displays the magnitude of a spatial phenomenon as color, usually cast over a map.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] In the image labeled "Spatial Heat Map Example," temperature is displayed by color range across a map of the world.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Color ranges from blue (cold) to red (hot).
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] A **grid heat map** displays magnitude as color in a two-dimensional matrix, with each dimension representing a category of trait and the color representing the magnitude of some measurement on the combined traits from each of the two categories.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] For example, one dimension might represent year, and the other dimension might represent month, and the value measured might be temperature.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] This heat map would show how temperature changed over the years in each month.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Grid heat maps are further categorized into two different types of matrices: clustered, and correlogram.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] In a grid heat map, colors are presented in a grid of a fixed size, with every cell in the grid also being an equal size and shape.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] The goal is to detect clustering, or suggest the presence of clusters.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] A spatial heat map is often used on maps or satellite imagery (see GIS), where there is no concept of cells, and instead the colors vary continuously.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Heat maps have a wide range of possibilities amongst applications due to their ability to simplify data and make for visually appealing to read data analysis.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Many applications using different types of heat maps are listed below.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Business Analysis: Heat maps are used in business analytics to give a visual representation about a company's current functioning, performance, and the need for improvements.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Heat maps are a way to analyze a company's existing data and update it to reflect growth and other specific efforts.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Heat maps visually appeal to team members and clients of the business or company.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Websites: There are many different ways heat maps are used within websites to determine a visiting users actions.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Typically, there are multiple heat maps used together to determine insight to a website on what are the best and worst performing elements on the page.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Some specific heat maps used for website analysis are listed below.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Exploratory Data Analysis: Working with small and large data sets, data scientists and data analysts look at and determine essential relationships and characteristics amongst different points in a data set as well as features of those data points.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Data scientists and analysts work with a team of others in different professions.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] The use of heat maps make for a visually easy way to summarize findings and main components.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] There are other ways to represent data, however heat maps can visualize these data points and their relationships in a high dimensional space without becoming too compact and visually unappealing.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Heat maps in data analysis, allow for specific variables of rows and/or columns on the axes and even on the diagonal.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Biology: In the biological field, heat maps are used to visually represent large and small sets of data.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] The focus is towards patterns and similarities in DNA, RNA, gene expression, etc.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Financial Analysis: The values of different product and assets fluctuate both rapidly and/or gradually over time.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] The need to log changes to the daily markets is imperative.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] It allows for the ability to draw predictions from patterns while being able to revisit past numerical data.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Heat maps are able to remove the tedious process and enable the user to visualize data points and compare amongst the different performers.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Geographical Visualization: Heat maps are used to visualize and display a geographic distribution of data.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Heat maps represent different densities of data points on a geographical map to help users see the intensities of certain phenomena and to show items of most or least importance.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Heat maps used in geographical visualization are sometimes confused with choropleth maps, but the difference comes with how certain data is presented which differentiate the two.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Sports: Heat maps can be used in many sports and can influence manager's and/or coaches decisions based on high and low densities of data displayed.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Users can identify patterns within the game, the strategies of opponents and one's own team, make more informed decisions benefitting the player, team, and business, and can enhance performance in different areas by identifying enhancement is needed.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Heat maps also visualize comparisons and relationships amongst different teams in the same sport or between different sports all together.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Cybersecurity: In intrusion detection systems and log analysis, heat maps are used to highlight unusual access patterns, port scanning attempts, and malicious IP clustering.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] They help SOC (Security Operations Center) analysts quickly spot anomalies in large datasets.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Urban Planning: Heat maps are used in urban planning to visualize traffic congestion, pedestrian flow, and environmental conditions for data-driven infrastructure development (Batty et al., 2012).
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Environmental heat maps track air quality and urban heat islands, guiding green space planning (EEA, 2021).
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Noise pollution heat maps aid zoning and mitigation near residential areas (EEA, 2020).
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Commercial planners use foot traffic heat maps to optimize retail layouts (SmartSantander, 2014).
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Integrated in smart city systems, these maps enhance livability, sustainability, and safety (Batty et al., 2012).
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Many different color schemes can be used to illustrate the heat map, with perceptual advantages and disadvantages for each.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Choosing a good color scheme is integral to accurately and effectively displaying data, whereas a poor color scheme can lead viewers to inaccurate conclusions or exclude those with color deficiencies from proper analysis of said data.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Rainbow color maps, while a common choice, suffer from both accessibility and data continuity concerns.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Rainbow maps pose a challenge for users with color vision deficiencies, particularly in those with issues distinguishing red and green – a condition affecting a significant portion of the population.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] In addition to accessibility issues, rainbow heat map colors are not perceptually uniform; equal increments in data values do not correspond to equal changes in color.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] The lack of uniformity can create misleading visual effects, like an artificial boundary or gradient.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] These effects can compromise the accuracy of effectiveness of the visualization.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] This example of the amplitude with the colors showcasing the phase angle can be hard to interpret with the entire rainbow of colors.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] In this case, the rainbow color scheme may cloud interpretation for those with color vision deficiencies or create confusion by some of the hard color boundaries across the diagram.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] To address these challenges, perceptually uniform color sets have been created to accommodate visual impairments and maintain consistent color differences proportional to differences in data.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Perceptually uniform color schemes are carefully designed to maintain consistent perceptual differences and offer a better viewing experience for viewers with color vision deficiencies.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] When implementing these color schemes into a heat map, designers must consider the data context and intended emphasis.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] These schemes follow three main patterns: sequential gradients (varying intensity of a single hue), diverging palettes (two contrasting hues with a neutral midpoint), and qualitative sets for categorical data.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Scientific visualization has produced several perceptually uniform color sets (like Viridis, Magma, and Cividis) that address both uniformity and accessibility concerns.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Device limitations can also significantly affect heat map visualization effectiveness.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] When displayed on low-resolution screens, highly detailed color gradients may appear pixelated or banded, reducing the quality of the visualization; this is known as color quantization, which can obscure or wrongly emphasize pieces of data.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] To mitigate these effects, designers should consider all devices that will display their heat map, and their color limitations.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Comprehensive testing and using a scheme with few colors is the safest bet when creating a heat map that will be viewed across multiple device types.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Grey-scale compatibility is essential for heat map accessibility, especially when considering print media, black and white only displays, or monochromatic vision.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] When converting to grey-scale, many color schemes will lose their distinctive data mappings, allowing for different values to appear identical in luminescence.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Grey-scale friendly color schemes are designed to incorporate contrast between data points even when color is removed, such as the "virdis" family.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Choropleth maps and heat maps are often used in place of one another incorrectly when referring to data visualized geographically.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Both techniques show the proportion of a variable of interest, but the two differ in how the boundaries for the variable's data aggregations are constructed.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] If the data were collected and aggregated using irregular boundaries, such as administrative units, then a heat map displaying that data will be the same as a choropleth map, encouraging confusion about how the two differ.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Choropleth maps show data grouped by geographic boundaries like countries, states, provinces or even floodplains.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Each region has a singular value, visualized by color intensity, shading or pattern.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] The figure on the right displaying a choropleth map showing the United States' population density by state may be used as an example.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] The figure illustrates a singular value (population) denoted by blue color intensity proportionate to the state's value relative to all other states' values, bounded by each state's border.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Similarly, heat maps may also visualize data over a geographic region.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] However, unlike choropleth maps, heat maps show the proportion of a variable over an arbitrary, but usually small grid size, independent of geographic boundaries.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] The figure on the right displaying a heat map of world population is an example.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] The figure illustrates a single value (population) bounded in an arbitrary grid (square kilometers) with each cell in the grid represented by a color intensity proportionate to the value of the cell relative to all other cells.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Some heat maps that are created using approximated regional data may show familiar geographic borders in the visualization where none really exist.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] The illusion of geographic borders is due to the existence of patterns within the dataset rather than the visualization technique.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] The figure on the right displaying a heat map of world population also contains this occurrence.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Areas in rural parts of the United States and South America may closely resemble familiar geographic borders in those regions.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] Another example of a heatmap over a geographic area is a visualization of lake effect snow around Buffalo, New York, in mid-October 2006.
[src:seaborn-viz/heat-map] This figure shows another usage of heat maps with geographic areas, and how useful they can be in showcasing the effects of weather on specific areas as opposed to countries or states.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] A **histogram** is a visual representation of the distribution of quantitative data.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] To construct a histogram, the first step is to "bin" (or "bucket") the range of values— divide the entire range of values into a series of intervals—and then count how many values fall into each interval.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The bins are usually specified as consecutive, non-overlapping intervals of a variable.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The bins (intervals) are adjacent and are typically (but not required to be) of equal size.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Histograms give a rough sense of the density of the underlying distribution of the data, and often for density estimation: estimating the probability density function of the underlying variable.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The total area of a histogram used for probability density is always normalized to 1.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] If the length of the intervals on the *x*-axis are all 1, then a histogram is identical to a relative frequency plot.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Histograms are sometimes confused with bar charts.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] In a histogram, each bin is for a different range of values, so altogether the histogram illustrates the distribution of values.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] But in a bar chart, each bar is for a different category of observations (e.g., each bar might be for a different population), so altogether the bar chart can be used to compare different categories.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Some authors recommend that bar charts always have gaps between the bars to clarify that they are not histograms.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The term *histogram* was first introduced by Karl Pearson, the founder of mathematical statistics, in lectures delivered in 1892 at University College London.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Pearson's term is sometimes incorrectly said to combine the Greek root γραμμα (*gramma*; 'figure' or 'drawing') with the root ἱστορία (historia; 'inquiry or 'history').
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Alternatively the root ἱστίον (*histion*) is also proposed, meaning 'web' or 'tissue' (as in histology, the study of biological tissue).
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Both of these etymologies are incorrect, and in fact Pearson, who knew Ancient Greek well, derived the term from a different if homophonous Greek root, ἱστός ('something set upright' or 'mast'), referring to the vertical bars in the graph.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Pearson's new term was embedded in a series of other analogous neologisms, such as *stigmogram* and *radiogram*.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Pearson himself noted in 1895 that, although the term *histogram* was new, the type of graph it designates was "a common form of graphical representation".
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] In fact the technique of using a bar graph to represent statistical measurements was devised by the Scottish economist, William Playfair, in his *Commercial and political atlas* (1786).
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The words used to describe the patterns in a histogram are: "symmetric", "skewed left" or "right", "unimodal", "bimodal" or "multimodal".
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] It is a good idea to plot the data using several different bin widths to learn more about it.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Here is an example on tips given in a restaurant.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Census Bureau found that there were 124 million people who work outside of their homes.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Using their data on the time occupied by travel to work, the table below shows the absolute number of people who responded with travel times "at least 30 but less than 35 minutes" is higher than the numbers for the categories above and below it.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] This is likely due to people rounding their reported journey time.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The problem of reporting values as somewhat arbitrarily rounded numbers is a common phenomenon when collecting data from people.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] This histogram shows the number of cases per unit interval as the height of each block, so that the area of each block is equal to the number of people in the survey who fall into its category.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The area under the curve represents the total number of cases (124 million).
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] This type of histogram shows absolute numbers, with Q in thousands.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] This histogram differs from the first only in the vertical scale.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The area of each block is the fraction of the total that each category represents, and the total area of all the bars is equal to 1 (the fraction meaning "all").
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The curve displayed is a simple density estimate.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] This version shows proportions, and is also known as a unit area histogram.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] In other words, a histogram represents a frequency distribution by means of rectangles whose widths represent class intervals and whose areas are proportional to the corresponding frequencies: the height of each is the average frequency density for the interval.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The intervals are placed together in order to show that the data represented by the histogram, while exclusive, is also contiguous.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] (E.g., in a histogram it is possible to have two connecting intervals of 10.5–20.5 and 20.5–33.5, but not two connecting intervals of 10.5–20.5 and 22.5–32.5.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The data used to construct a histogram are generated via a function *m**i* that counts the number of observations that fall into each of the disjoint categories (known as *bins*).
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] A histogram can be thought of as a simplistic kernel density estimation, which uses a kernel to smooth frequencies over the bins.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] This yields a smoother probability density function, which will in general more accurately reflect distribution of the underlying variable.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The density estimate could be plotted as an alternative to the histogram, and is usually drawn as a curve rather than a set of boxes.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Histograms are nevertheless preferred in applications, when their statistical properties need to be modeled.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The correlated variation of a kernel density estimate is very difficult to describe mathematically, while it is simple for a histogram where each bin varies independently.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] An alternative to kernel density estimation is the average shifted histogram, which is fast to compute and gives a smooth curve estimate of the density without using kernels.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] A cumulative histogram: a mapping that counts the cumulative number of observations in all of the bins up to the specified bin.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] There is no "best" number of bins, and different bin sizes can reveal different features of the data.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Grouping data is at least as old as Graunt's work in the 17th century, but no systematic guidelines were given until Sturges's work in 1926.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Using wider bins where the density of the underlying data points is low reduces noise due to sampling randomness; using narrower bins where the density is high (so the signal drowns the noise) gives greater precision to the density estimation.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Thus varying the bin-width within a histogram can be beneficial.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Nonetheless, equal-width bins are widely used.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Some theoreticians have attempted to determine an optimal number of bins, but these methods generally make strong assumptions about the shape of the distribution.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Depending on the actual data distribution and the goals of the analysis, different bin widths may be appropriate, so experimentation is usually needed to determine an appropriate width.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] There are, however, various useful guidelines and rules of thumb.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The braces indicate the ceiling function.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] which takes the square root of the number of data points in the sample and rounds to the next integer.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] This rule is suggested by a number of elementary statistics textbooks and widely implemented in many software packages.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Sturges's rule is derived from a binomial distribution and implicitly assumes an approximately normal distribution.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Sturges's formula implicitly bases bin sizes on the range of the data, and can perform poorly if *n* < 30, because the number of bins will be small—less than seven—and unlikely to show trends in the data well.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] On the other extreme, Sturges's formula may overestimate bin width for very large datasets, resulting in oversmoothed histograms.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] It may also perform poorly if the data are not normally distributed.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] When compared to Scott's rule and the Terrell-Scott rule, two other widely accepted formulas for histogram bins, the output of Sturges's formula is closest when *n* ≈ 100.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The Rice rule is presented as a simple alternative to Sturges's rule.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Doane's formula is a modification of Sturges's formula which attempts to improve its performance with non-normal data.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] where ${\hat {\sigma }}$ is the sample standard deviation.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Scott's normal reference rule is optimal for random samples of normally distributed data, in the sense that it minimizes the integrated mean squared error of the density estimate.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] This is the default rule used in Microsoft Excel.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The Terrell–Scott rule is not a normal reference rule.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] It gives the minimum number of bins required for an asymptotically optimal histogram, where optimality is measured by the integrated mean squared error.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The bound is derived by finding the 'smoothest' possible density, which turns out to be ${\frac {3}{4}}(1-x^{2})$ .
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Any other density will require more bins, hence the above estimate is also referred to as the 'oversmoothed' rule.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The similarity of the formulas and the fact that Terrell and Scott were at Rice University when the proposed it suggests that this is also the origin of the Rice rule.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] which is based on the interquartile range, denoted by IQR.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] It replaces 3.5σ of Scott's rule with 2 IQR, which is less sensitive than the standard deviation to outliers in data.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Here, $N_{k}$ is the number of datapoints in the *k*th bin, and choosing the value of *h* that minimizes *J* will minimize integrated mean squared error.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Rather than choosing evenly spaced bins, for some applications it is preferable to vary the bin width.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] A common case is to choose *equiprobable bins*, where the number of samples in each bin is expected to be approximately equal.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] The bins may be chosen according to some known distribution or may be chosen based on the data so that each bin has $\approx n/k$ samples.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] When plotting the histogram, the *frequency density* is used for the dependent axis.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] While all bins have approximately equal area, the heights of the histogram approximate the density distribution.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] This choice of bins is motivated by maximizing the power of a Pearson chi-squared test testing whether the bins do contain equal numbers of samples.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Where $\Phi ^{-1}$ is the probit function.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Following this rule for $\alpha =0.05$ would give between $1.88n^{2/5}$ and $3.77n^{2/5}$ ; the coefficient of 2 is chosen as an easy-to-remember value from this broad optimum.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] A good reason why the number of bins should be proportional to ${\sqrt[{3}]{n}}$ is the following: suppose that the data are obtained as n independent realizations of a bounded probability distribution with smooth density.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Then the histogram remains equally "rugged" as n tends to infinity.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] If s is the "width" of the distribution (e. g., the standard deviation or the inter-quartile range), then the number of units in a bin (the frequency) is of order $nh/s$ and the *relative* standard error is of order ${\sqrt {s/(nh)}}$ .
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] Compared to the next bin, the relative change of the frequency is of order $h/s$ provided that the derivative of the density is non-zero.
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] These two are of the same order if h is of order $s/{\sqrt[{3}]{n}}$ , so that k is of order ${\sqrt[{3}]{n}}$ .
[src:seaborn-viz/histogram] This simple cubic root choice can also be applied to bins with non-constant widths.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Seaborn is a library for making statistical graphics in Python.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] It builds on top of matplotlib and integrates closely with pandas data structures.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Seaborn helps you explore and understand your data.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Its plotting functions operate on dataframes and arrays containing whole datasets and internally perform the necessary semantic mapping and statistical aggregation to produce informative plots.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Its dataset-oriented, declarative API lets you focus on what the different elements of your plots mean, rather than on the details of how to draw them.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Seaborn is the only library we need to import for this simple example.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] By convention, it is imported with the shorthand `sns`.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Behind the scenes, seaborn uses matplotlib to draw its plots.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] For interactive work, it’s recommended to use a Jupyter/IPython interface in matplotlib mode, or else you’ll have to call `matplotlib.pyplot.show()` when you want to see the plot.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] This uses the matplotlib rcParam system and will affect how all matplotlib plots look, even if you don’t make them with seaborn.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Beyond the default theme, there are several other options, and you can independently control the style and scaling of the plot to quickly translate your work between presentation contexts (e.g., making a version of your figure that will have readable fonts when projected during a talk).
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] If you like the matplotlib defaults or prefer a different theme, you can skip this step and still use the seaborn plotting functions.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Most code in the docs will use the `load_dataset()` function to get quick access to an example dataset.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] There’s nothing special about these datasets: they are just pandas dataframes, and we could have loaded them with `pandas.read_csv()` or built them by hand.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Most of the examples in the documentation will specify data using pandas dataframes, but seaborn is very flexible about the data structures that it accepts.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] This plot shows the relationship between five variables in the tips dataset using a single call to the seaborn function `relplot()`.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Notice how we provided only the names of the variables and their roles in the plot.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Unlike when using matplotlib directly, it wasn’t necessary to specify attributes of the plot elements in terms of the color values or marker codes.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Behind the scenes, seaborn handled the translation from values in the dataframe to arguments that matplotlib understands.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] This declarative approach lets you stay focused on the questions that you want to answer, rather than on the details of how to control matplotlib.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] There is no universally best way to visualize data.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Different questions are best answered by different plots.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Seaborn makes it easy to switch between different visual representations by using a consistent dataset-oriented API.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] The function `relplot()` is named that way because it is designed to visualize many different statistical *relationships*.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] While scatter plots are often effective, relationships where one variable represents a measure of time are better represented by a line.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Notice how the `size` and `style` parameters are used in both the scatter and line plots, but they affect the two visualizations differently: changing the marker area and symbol in the scatter plot vs the line width and dashing in the line plot.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] We did not need to keep those details in mind, letting us focus on the overall structure of the plot and the information we want it to convey.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Often, we are interested in the *average* value of one variable as a function of other variables.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] When statistical values are estimated, seaborn will use bootstrapping to compute confidence intervals and draw error bars representing the uncertainty of the estimate.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Statistical estimation in seaborn goes beyond descriptive statistics.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Statistical analyses require knowledge about the distribution of variables in your dataset.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] The seaborn function `displot()` supports several approaches to visualizing distributions.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Several specialized plot types in seaborn are oriented towards visualizing categorical data.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] They can be accessed through `catplot()`.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] These plots offer different levels of granularity.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Some seaborn functions combine multiple kinds of plots to quickly give informative summaries of a dataset.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] One, `jointplot()`, focuses on a single relationship.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] These tools work by combining axes-level plotting functions with objects that manage the layout of the figure, linking the structure of a dataset to a grid of axes.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Seaborn creates complete graphics with a single function call: when possible, its functions will automatically add informative axis labels and legends that explain the semantic mappings in the plot.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] In many cases, seaborn will also choose default values for its parameters based on characteristics of the data.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] For example, the color mappings that we have seen so far used distinct hues (blue, orange, and sometimes green) to represent different levels of the categorical variables assigned to `hue`.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] When you’re ready to share or publish your work, you’ll probably want to polish the figure beyond what the defaults achieve.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Seaborn allows for several levels of customization.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] It defines multiple built-in themes that apply to all figures, its functions have standardized parameters that can modify the semantic mappings for each plot, and additional keyword arguments are passed down to the underlying matplotlib artists, allowing even more control.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Seaborn’s integration with matplotlib allows you to use it across the many environments that matplotlib supports, including exploratory analysis in notebooks, real-time interaction in GUI applications, and archival output in a number of raster and vector formats.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] While you can be productive using only seaborn functions, full customization of your graphics will require some knowledge of matplotlib’s concepts and API.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] One aspect of the learning curve for new users of seaborn will be knowing when dropping down to the matplotlib layer is necessary to achieve a particular customization.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] On the other hand, users coming from matplotlib will find that much of their knowledge transfers.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Matplotlib has a comprehensive and powerful API; just about any attribute of the figure can be changed to your liking.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] A combination of seaborn’s high-level interface and matplotlib’s deep customizability will allow you both to quickly explore your data and to create graphics that can be tailored into a publication quality final product.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] You have a few options for where to go next.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] You might first want to learn how to install seaborn.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Once that’s done, you can browse the example gallery to get a broader sense for what kind of graphics seaborn can produce.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] Or you can read through the rest of the user guide and tutorial for a deeper discussion of the different tools and what they are designed to accomplish.
[src:seaborn-viz/introduction] If you have a specific plot in mind and want to know how to make it, you could check out the API reference, which documents each function’s parameters and shows many examples to illustrate usage.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] Statistical analysis is a process of understanding how variables in a dataset relate to each other and how those relationships depend on other variables.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] Visualization can be a core component of this process because, when data are visualized properly, the human visual system can see trends and patterns that indicate a relationship.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] We will discuss three seaborn functions in this tutorial.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] The one we will use most is `relplot()`.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] This is a figure-level function for visualizing statistical relationships using two common approaches: scatter plots and line plots.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] As we will see, these functions can be quite illuminating because they use simple and easily-understood representations of data that can nevertheless represent complex dataset structures.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] They can do so because they plot two-dimensional graphics that can be enhanced by mapping up to three additional variables using the semantics of hue, size, and style.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] The scatter plot is a mainstay of statistical visualization.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] It depicts the joint distribution of two variables using a cloud of points, where each point represents an observation in the dataset.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] This depiction allows the eye to infer a substantial amount of information about whether there is any meaningful relationship between them.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] There are several ways to draw a scatter plot in seaborn.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] The most basic, which should be used when both variables are numeric, is the `scatterplot()` function.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] In the categorical visualization tutorial, we will see specialized tools for using scatterplots to visualize categorical data.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] While the points are plotted in two dimensions, another dimension can be added to the plot by coloring the points according to a third variable.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] It’s also possible to represent four variables by changing the hue and style of each point independently.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] In the examples above, the hue semantic was categorical, so the default qualitative palette was applied.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] In both cases, you can customize the color palette.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] Unlike with `matplotlib.pyplot.scatter()`, the literal value of the variable is not used to pick the area of the point.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] Instead, the range of values in data units is normalized into a range in area units.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] More examples for customizing how the different semantics are used to show statistical relationships are shown in the `scatterplot()` API examples.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] Scatter plots are highly effective, but there is no universally optimal type of visualisation.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] Instead, the visual representation should be adapted for the specifics of the dataset and to the question you are trying to answer with the plot.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] With some datasets, you may want to understand changes in one variable as a function of time, or a similarly continuous variable.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] In this situation, a good choice is to draw a line plot.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] More complex datasets will have multiple measurements for the same value of the `x` variable.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] The confidence intervals are computed using bootstrapping, which can be time-intensive for larger datasets.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] To turn off aggregation altogether, set the `estimator` parameter to `None` This might produce a strange effect when the data have multiple observations at each point.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] The `lineplot()` function has the same flexibility as `scatterplot()`: it can show up to three additional variables by modifying the hue, size, and style of the plot elements.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] It does so using the same API as `scatterplot()`, meaning that we don’t need to stop and think about the parameters that control the look of lines vs. points in matplotlib.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] Using semantics in `lineplot()` will also determine how the data get aggregated.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] For example, adding a hue semantic with two levels splits the plot into two lines and error bands, coloring each to indicate which subset of the data they correspond to.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] As with scatter plots, be cautious about making line plots using multiple semantics.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] While sometimes informative, they can also be difficult to parse and interpret.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] But even when you are only examining changes across one additional variable, it can be useful to alter both the color and style of the lines.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] When you are working with repeated measures data (that is, you have units that were sampled multiple times), you can also plot each sampling unit separately without distinguishing them through semantics.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] It may happen that, even though the `hue` variable is numeric, it is poorly represented by a linear color scale.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] That’s the case here, where the levels of the `hue` variable are logarithmically scaled.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] While the `size` variable will typically be numeric, it’s also possible to map a categorical variable with the width of the lines.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] Be cautious when doing so, because it will be difficult to distinguish much more than “thick” vs “thin” lines.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] Because `lineplot()` assumes that you are most often trying to draw `y` as a function of `x`, the default behavior is to sort the data by the `x` values before plotting.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] We’ve emphasized in this tutorial that, while these functions *can* show several semantic variables at once, it’s not always effective to do so.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] But what about when you do want to understand how a relationship between two variables depends on more than one other variable?
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] The best approach may be to make more than one plot.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] Because `relplot()` is based on the `FacetGrid`, this is easy to do.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] To show the influence of an additional variable, instead of assigning it to one of the semantic roles in the plot, use it to “facet” the visualization.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] You can also show the influence of two variables this way: one by faceting on the columns and one by faceting on the rows.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] As you start adding more variables to the grid, you may want to decrease the figure size.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] These visualizations, which are sometimes called “lattice” plots or “small-multiples”, are very effective because they present the data in a format that makes it easy for the eye to detect both overall patterns and deviations from those patterns.
[src:seaborn-viz/relational] While you should make use of the flexibility afforded by `scatterplot()` and `relplot()`, always try to keep in mind that several simple plots are usually more effective than one complex plot.
[src:seaborn-viz/statistical-graphics] Whereas statistics and data analysis procedures generally yield their output in numeric or tabular form, graphical techniques allow such results to be displayed in some sort of pictorial form.
[src:seaborn-viz/statistical-graphics] They include plots such as scatter plots, histograms, probability plots, spaghetti plots, residual plots, box plots, block plots and biplots.
[src:seaborn-viz/statistical-graphics] Exploratory data analysis (EDA) relies heavily on such techniques.
[src:seaborn-viz/statistical-graphics] They can also provide insight into a data set to help with testing assumptions, model selection and regression model validation, estimator selection, relationship identification, factor effect determination, and outlier detection.
[src:seaborn-viz/statistical-graphics] In addition, the choice of appropriate statistical graphics can provide a convincing means of communicating the underlying message that is present in the data to others.
[src:seaborn-viz/statistical-graphics] If one is not using statistical graphics, then one is forfeiting insight into one or more aspects of the underlying structure of the data.
[src:seaborn-viz/statistical-graphics] Statistical graphics have been central to the development of science and date to the earliest attempts to analyse data.
[src:seaborn-viz/statistical-graphics] Many familiar forms, including bivariate plots, statistical maps, bar charts, and coordinate paper were used in the 18th century.
[src:seaborn-viz/statistical-graphics] Since the 1970s statistical graphics have been re-emerging as an important analytic tool with the revitalisation of computer graphics and related technologies.
[src:seaborn-viz/statistical-graphics] See the plots page for many more examples of statistical graphics.
